segments.text: The plan was particularly effective and accepted by the vast majority of the people in the city.
And not only that, whenever we had a bond issue and it was known that the bond issue was in accordance with the plan, it passed overwhelmingly.
And every time
We approached a state or federal agency.
We showed them the plan, showed them what the city was doing, and then outlined the part that we thought that particular agency should be responsible for.
And invariably,
we came away with the acceptance of the agency of our request and they granted the request and they followed the plan.
So the plan was followed very conscientiously from the very beginning.
The only thing that was not done was the community would not accept urban renewal.
So the plan was implemented
financed with all the different agencies participating.
The Area Development Committee decided in 1949 and 1950 to proceed with the plan.
It took three years to complete the plan, and it was published in 1953.
The plan was virtually completed in the early 1960s.
All of the proposals had been accomplished in the early 1960s.
And so the Area Development Committee, which remained active the full time, decided that an update of the plan was needed, that they needed new goals and objectives.
So they went back again to the Bartholomew Organization,
and asked them to update the plan.
That firm went to work and completed their plan and submitted the final report in December 1967.
The second plan
was technically very well done.
The goals and objectives were not as clear as in the original plan.
That plan is still being used as a guide.
And a number of the things have been accomplished.
one of which was Corpus Christi Beach, or North Beach, the area north of the ship channel to Nueces and Nueces Bay.
A request was made to the Corps of Engineers to restore the beach.
A great deal of demolition of substandard dwellings, Corpus Christi's own version of urban renewal without federal assistance, was undertaken.
And a great many of the substandard housing that existed on that beach was eliminated.
An act was secured.
through Congress for the use of the Beach Erosion Act to restore the sand beach in this area that had eroded back to and even under some of the buildings.
It took 10 years of constant effort
to get this plan completed and implemented through the Corps of Engineers.
The restoration of the beach was accomplished in about 1978 or 1979.

Another one of the objectives was the construction of a dam, another water supply, because the lake at Mathis had a limited capacity and could not accommodate the expanding industrial and domestic demand for water.
Controversy arose as to the location of this dam.
The area development plan did recommend the site that is now being completed for the new dam at Cho Canyon.
The dam was partially financed through the Bureau of Reclamation.
The gates of this dam are going to be closed within the next two months, and this lake will furnish a water supply well into the 2020s.
This is just finished now.
That's just finished.
That's another accomplishment of the plan.
Bill, tell me, how did this project that I don't know very much about, the goals for Corpus Christi, how did that relate?
The what?
Goals for Corpus Christi project.
Goals for Corpus Christi?
How did that relate to the Area Development Committee's work?
Well, the Area Development Committee did
support the program for the goals of Corpus Christi.
A number of committees were established, and the goals were outlined and published.
But unfortunately, not very much has been done to follow up on it.
It's a nice book, and quite a few people have it, but very little reference is ever made to it now.
Not nearly as effective as the one they had in Dallas.
The Area Development Committee did give support to that.
It was a more or less independent effort, aside from the Area Development Committee.
Yes.
They had their own
They had their own employee that did all the groundwork and assembled it and put it together.
Did it have any direct relationship to the planning department?
No, no.
And what about any direct relationship to municipal government?
Well, the mayor and the council gave it encouragement.
But I don't think they did anything to really implement it.
Nor the county government, nor the school district.
Neither of them did anything very spectacular to support it.
This comprehensive plan did contain several things that had a program for the
restoration of the central city.
It had a plan for an outer belt parkway system at the Cayo del Oso, which is a creek on the perimeter of the city.
Nothing has been done with that except there have been some committees that have been working at it.
But that's one of the goals and one of the challenges that still remain for the city to do.
Major changes in land use or the school system.
There was a plan for
the Oso Bay to fill in sections of it and develop it.
This was unacceptable to the environmental interests and has not been accomplished.
There was a feasibility study made to determine if a
offshore roadway could be built from downtown to the south end of the city.
This proved to be not feasible.
Offshore road was several thousand feet off the shore.
It had islands in connection with it that were
could be developed, both as residential and recreational, with connections into the shoreline.
But the plan was entirely too expensive and was environmentally not acceptable.
In 1962, thereabouts,
The federal government enacted the federal government provided through the U.S. Bureau of Public Roads federal highway agency the opportunity to prepare
transportation plans for cities.
Corpus Christi was the first city in the United States to apply for such a plan.
The local district engineer, Theo Foster, was entirely sympathetic and agreed to help us go before the State Highway Commission
and seek approval of the preparation of this plan.
Local people went there, the political leaders.
The Area Development Committee was interested and helped, but did not take an active part.
We did get approval of the State Highway Department.
to proceed.
The State Highway Department had no planners on the staff, but assigned some very good engineers that were progressive and wanted to prepare a good plan.
The city and the county
the navigation district, and all agreed to assist in the preparation of this plan by providing technical assistance and staff.
As city planner, I was assigned to this committee, and we had at least two
members of our planning staff that worked with the highway engineers that were assigned to this.
Do you remember their names?
One of them was Earl Goetsch.
How does he spell that?
G-O-E-T-S-C-H.
He was a senior planner.
And we had the traffic engineer, Tom Stewart.
We had public works director.
And we had the right to call in as we needed them.
of the other city staff.
The county engineer was on this, Jesse Lawrence participated, and we had regular meetings.
And we outlined what should be in the transportation plan.
And this was a pioneering effort because it was, and we were considered the guinea pig.
And so we prepared our outline, which contained such subjects as economic factors, population, land use, the inventory of transportation facilities,
studies on travel patterns, terminals and transfer facilities, traffic engineering, community controls, financial resources, and methods of financing the plan.
And then there was a long range plan for the major street system.
proposed.
This plan was prepared and completed in 1964.
And as required by the federal legislation, the city council was asked to adopt it.
And they did.
And they
The plan was very well followed, particularly as to major streets and thoroughfares.
But each year, in accordance with the federal legislation, this plan was to be updated.
So a supplement was prepared each year on this plan.

Today, very little is being done with updating the comprehensive city plan, but through the transportation planning and the various committees that were established at that time, there has been some updating done.
The city manager
during the period from 1967 to 1980, was not interested in updating the comprehensive plan.
Why was that?
Well, he felt that
Most of the updating could be done on an administrative basis through the city manager's office.
Why did you feel that the city manager's office was qualified to do the updating of professional planning material?
Well, the city manager himself was a graduate of a planning school.
His degree was in administration, but he had taken all of the comprehensive planning at Cornell.
Well, what did the planning director have to say about this arrangement?
The planning director informally did proceed with some
updating of the plans that was me but as separate reports as not as part of the comprehensive plan separate report on specific projects mostly Marvin Townsend he was a very competent city manager
When did hewas he hired by the city?
Yes, he was hired by the city.
When?
Oh, he was started out in the fifties, and he came up through the ranks to be city manager.
And then he left about He left in 1981.
Who is the city manager now?
The city manager now is Mr. Martin, who was brought in here and formerly city manager for Evanston, Illinois.
He's just getting started.
I know nothing about his interest in planning.
Today, Michael Gunning.
who is the transportation planner, does a great deal of planning through that.
For instance, all subdivisions have to be approved by the transportation planning section as it relates to streets and highways.
a generation of traffic and land use.
I retired in 1973 from the city after 27 years of continuous services director of planning.
My successor
was Mr. Larry Winger.
But there was this change in the administrative organization.
There was a man that was called Director of Planning and Urban Development.
And this man's
principal responsibilities were to implement the federal programs that were being used by the city, housing programs and welfare programs and programs of that kind.
Mr. Wenger, who was called the planner,
continued to do essentially what I had done for 27 years.
There has been a later revision of the administrative plan, and Mr. Wenger is now the director of planning again.
Very little is being done now.
Do they still have a director of urban development?
Well, yes, there's still one there, and that's at a higher level.
I see.
That's in the manager's office?
That's in the manager's office, and Mr. Winger is responsible to him.
Prior to that time, when I was director of planning, I was directly responsible to the city manager.
The Area Development Committee is still in existence.
It is an autonomous committee of the Chamber of Commerce.
They select their own membership, and they're appointed for long terms, six years, I think.
They provide their own financing for anything they do.
The only thing that I know of recently that they have done, they supported a review of the plan for the Bayfront by Sasaki Walker Organization.
Their man came down here.
and made some study and made a few suggestions which were constructive.
OK.
Bill, I'm going to be interviewing several other people in Corpus Christi, and I'd like to have any of your ideas on any additional persons.
But one person that comes to mind is Ruth Gill, who was on the city council for some time, and now she's with the COG.
And then Tom Brown, for his role as executive director of the COG.
And I understand that he's going to be transferring over to the navigation system.
To where?
Navigation District.
And I was thinking I should probably interview Larry and Michael Gunning.
Yeah.
And just get their views on things.
Yeah, they're both very good people to get their views on.
Ruth Gill was a very active person on the city council.
She was very sympathetic to the planning programs.
She eventually became active in the Council of Governments, and she has been chairman of a good many committees.
One of the committees she was chairman of was the Oso Parkway Committee.
And she was trying to find a means to implement that plan.
And as far as I know, the committee is still active.
I'm a member of that committee.
Well, I think the city is a much better place because we had a city plan, a good comprehensive plan that was
a plan of the people, the leadership, both economic and political, were able to work together, as well as a big segment of the citizens.
And as far as I have been able to learn, that they're very happy with
the results of the plan.
We're in the office of Michael Gunning, senior planner for the planning department of Corpus Christi.
This is the 29th of May, 1982.
and Michael is going to tell us a little bit about his personal, professional history, how he came to be in Corpus Christi, and then go on with some topics that have already been discussed.
Michael?
Bob, I happen to be one of those planners who walked into a,
a temporary job.
It was at least temporary in my mind when I first took the job under Jonathan Cunningham with the Department of Planning with the city of El Paso.
I had graduated from Texas Western College, now the University of Texas at El Paso in 1966.
I went ahead and completed one year of law school at Texas Tech University and returned home in the summer of 68 and married and
shortly thereafter my wife became pregnant with her first child, not wanting to go back to law school, completely broke.
I ran into a few friends of mine who had started work with the Department of Planning, Jim Sorensen primarily, who told me that I ought to come in and speak with Jonathan Cunningham.
And I did, and Jonathan hired me basically on the spot to
to work with some projects, special research projects that he had set up.
And I started the Department of Planning as a planning technician for $425 a month.
And that was back in September of 1968.
I stayed with the city of El Paso until March of 1973.
And during my years with El Paso,
working with John Cunningham and under his senior planners and assistant director, Bill Adams, and at one time Nestor Valencia.
He had moved me through every aspect of planning that one could imagine.
My first job was to update to a community facilities inventory for the city of El Paso, which was very surprising being a life, a long resident of El Paso and
and having to do the community facilities inventory taught me that I really didn't know as much about the city as I originally thought.
And the second project John put me on was to coordinate the updating of all the land uses in El Paso, which was a very eye-opening type of assignment.
And it really made me very familiar with the city and some of its problems.
And with the completion of the plan.
